Server-side rendering (SSR) patterns are fully supported with Appwrite. 
SSR is a technique used in web development where web pages are 
generated on the server instead of in the browser browser. 
This differs from client-side rendering, where the web content is generated in the user's browser using JavaScript.

You can use Appwrite with many SSR frameworks like Next.js, SvelteKit, Nuxt, Gatsby, Remix, and more.
This guide will walk you through the process of implementing SSR with Appwrite.

# SSR authentication flow {% #ssr-auth-flow %}
In client-side rendered web apps, a [Client SDK](/docs/sdks#client) is used to perform authentication directly from the client's web browser.
On server-side rendered web apps, a [Server SDK](/docs/sdks#server) is used to handle authentication against Appwrite, which means
authentication information is first passed from the client's web browser to your server, and the server authenticates against Appwrite.

